Member-only story

A long dependency list is often a sign that your component knows too much.

6 min read
1 day ago

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Angular’s Dependency Injection system makes consuming services extremely convenient.
Need customer data?
Inject CustomerApiService.
Need permissions?
Inject PermissionService.
Need notifications?
Inject NotificationService.
Need analytics?
Inject AnalyticsService.
Each dependency looks reasonable on its own.
But over time, a component can quietly become the coordination layer for an entire feature.
@Component({
selector: 'app-customer-page',
templateUrl: './customer-page.html'
})
export class CustomerPageComponent {
private readonly customerApi = inject(CustomerApiService);
private readonly customerStore = inject(CustomerStore);
private readonly permissions = inject(PermissionService);
private readonly notifications = inject(NotificationService);
private readonly analytics = inject(AnalyticsService);
private readonly featureFlags = inject(FeatureFlagService);
private readonly logger = inject(LoggerService);
